<tr>
<td valign="MIDDLE"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="000000">I agree and disagree.<p>

Everquest is both based and unbased on reality.<p>

For instance, certain truths we've come to accept in reality exist in Norrath.  Gravity, day and night, the requirement of food and drink, etc.<p>

On the other hand, certain truths are absent.  Your character does not require sleep.  Depending on your ability to stay awake, your character could go several weeks or months without sleep.  I don't care how many magic shows you watch, none of those guys are actually conjuring up earth elementals, levitating themselves, or throwing fireballs at nearby rats.<p>

So while I am quite displeased with the speed of my fists, I can accept the argument that Monks are waiting for an opening before they strike, if Verant ever chose to use it.  A guy with a sword is much more likely to swing it without regard for the effect than a guy swinging his fist.  It's HIS fist, if he doesn't hit the right spot, or Gods forbid the other guy parries with a sword, HE gets hurt.  If the sword hits the ultra-hard spot of the armor, or gets slapped away by another sword or axe, the guy swinging it doesn't care.  The sword doesn't feel pain.<p>

A martial artist can hit many times in a second, and only another martial artist is likely to dodge or deflect the blows he throws.  However, if a martial artist is fighting a swordsman, the fight is likely going to be a lot of waiting for the opening, and then a quick series of "let me re-arrange your body parts" blows.  So you dance around, find the opening, hit him several times, and then step back before that sword comes down and removes one of your all-important fists.<p>

It's simple.  You fight differently when it's one of your body parts that's being thrown at the enemy.  There's different rules, different considerations.  Instead of coding an entirely new set of rules for monkly combat, Verant has used a way that imperfectly simulates it within the current system.<p>

So what is my opinion?  I think that fist should be faster.  They weigh less, and you're a lot more familiar with them than you are with a weapon.  However, I'm not going to throw a punch every time I'm able.  I want to make sure that when I pull my arm back my fist is still there, and isn't broken, sliced, or otherwise mangled.  So while I think that fists easily rate an attack speed around 12, I do not think that any intelligent monk would attack at that speed.  As to what the attack speed of fists should actually start at, I can't say.  I just think it should be faster than it is, but slower than it would be if measured in reality.<p>

Tygrex,<br>
Humble Brother of the Silent Fist Order.</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="DDDDDD">
